source: Beilstein F. K.; Beilsteins Handbuch der Organischen Chemie. Springer; Berlin; 1972.
Reason: Methyl 3-bromobenzoate molecular structure can be broken down to its basic functional groups and compared to known substances to predict its melting point. The basic unit benzene has a melting point of 5.5°C. Bromine, as a bromo substituent on the benzene ring, is a heavy atom that may increase the melting point by contributing to the molecular weight and providing London dispersion forces; this might contribute an increase of +40°C. The ester group (C(=O)OC), has the ability to form dipole-dipole interactions and potentially weak hydrogen bonds with moisture in the environment, leading to an increase of about +50°C to the melting point. However, the ortho effect of the substituents being in positions that can influence each other, especially steric hinderance of the bromine with the ester group, might actually reduce the effectiveness of these interactions and decrease the melting point slightly by -10°C. Combining these effects should give a reasonable estimate of the melting point for the compound.
